Text mining in R

Nic Rivers

November 22, 2019

Introduction

  • Increasingly, researchers are making use of data extracted from text in quantitative studies.
  • Examples:
    • Baylis (2019) on the effects of temperature on profanity and sentiment expressed on Twitter (https://www.patrickbaylis.com/pdf/Baylis_TT.pdf).
    • Yzaguirre et al.(2016) find and geo-locate historical flooding events in Nova Scotia using automated Newspaper search (https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1755-1315/34/1/012043/pdf)

Extracting data from text

Madam Speaker, the opioid crisis is growing every year. The number of deaths due to overdose are increasing at an alarming rate. In 2016, there were just over 3,000 opioid related deaths in Canada. In 2017, the number jumped to almost 4,000. That is a 33% increase over just one year. These are preventable deaths. When will we see the real plan from the government to address this very troubling issue? Conservative MP Bob Saroya, Question Period 2018-10-26.

  • What data can we extract from text?
    • Topic
    • Sentiment
    • Measures of speech complexity (word count, syllable count, readability)

Finding words in text

library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
saroya_long <- "Madam Speaker, the opioid crisis is growing every year. The number of deaths due to overdose are increasing at an alarming rate. In 2016, there were just over 3,000 opioid related deaths in Canada. In 2017, the number jumped to almost 4,000. That is a 33% increase over just one year. These are preventable deaths. When will we see the real plan from the government to address this very troubling issue?"
# A shorter string
saroya <- "Madam Speaker, the opioid crisis is growing every year."

# Does the text contain the word "opioid"?
str_detect(saroya, "opioid")
## [1] TRUE
# Does the text contain the word "climate change"?
str_detect(saroya, "climate change")
## [1] FALSE

Dealing with cases

# Dealing with cases
str_detect(saroya, "OPIOID")
## [1] FALSE
str_detect(saroya, regex("OPIOID", ignore_case = TRUE))
## [1] TRUE
# Wildcards
str_detect(saroya, ".eak.")
## [1] TRUE

Tidy text

The tidytext library allows for processing text by converting text into tidy data: one token word, sentence, etc. per line. The unnest_tokens() function separates text into tokens.

tibble(text = saroya) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)
## # A tibble: 9 x 1
##   word   
##   <chr>  
## 1 madam  
## 2 speaker
## 3 the    
## 4 opioid 
## 5 crisis 
## 6 is     
## 7 growing
## 8 every  
## 9 year

Counting word occurrences

Once we have the text tokenized, we can use our usual data handling tools. For example, we can count occurrences of words.

tibble(text = saroya_long) %>%
   unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
   group_by(word) %>%
   summarise(n=n()) %>% arrange(desc(n)) %>% top_n(3)
## Selecting by n
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##   word       n
##   <chr>  <int>
## 1 the        5
## 2 deaths     3
## 3 in         3
## 4 to         3

Getting rid of common (stop) words

We arent usually interested in words like the, and, is, etc. These are stored in a data frame called stop_words. (You can examine stop_words).

We can get rid of them using anti_join.

tibble(text = saroya_long) %>%
   unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
   group_by(word) %>%
   summarise(n=n()) %>% arrange(desc(n)) %>% top_n(2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   word       n
##   <chr>  <int>
## 1 deaths     3
## 2 opioid     2

Topic analysis in multiple texts

It is straightforward to apply these techniques to many texts at the same time thats where they get powerful. For example, rather than looking at just one MP speech, lets look at them all (for 2018). The data frame speeches contains all the speeches made in the House of Commons (in 2018).

Frequency of speeches on a given topic

Lets find all the speeches containg the word carbon tax. Then lets find the proportion of all the speeches by each party that contain the word carbon tax. The conservatives spent a lot of time talking about the carbon tax in 2018.

speeches %>%
  mutate(contains_word = str_detect(speechtext, regex("carbon tax", ignore_case = TRUE))) %>%
  group_by(speakerparty) %>%
  filter(speakerparty %in% c("Conservative", "New Democratic Party", "Liberal"),
         !is.na(contains_word)) %>%
  summarise(freq = sum(contains_word) / n()) %>%
  mutate(freq = scales::percent(freq))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   speakerparty         freq 
##   <chr>                <chr>
## 1 Conservative         8.71%
## 2 Liberal              0.33%
## 3 New Democratic Party 1.06%

tidytext integrates with ggplot

Speeches on carbon tax over time

library(lubridate) # for dealing with dates
## Warning: package 'lubridate' was built under R version 3.4.4
date_ct <- speeches %>%
  mutate(contains_word = str_detect(speechtext, regex("carbon tax", ignore_case = TRUE)),
         month_label = month(speechdate, label=TRUE),
         month = month(speechdate)) %>%
  group_by(speakerparty, month, month_label) %>%
  filter(speakerparty %in% c("Conservative", "New Democratic Party", "Liberal"),
         !is.na(contains_word)) %>%
  summarise(freq = sum(contains_word) / n())
ggplot(date_ct, aes(x=month_label, y=freq, colour=speakerparty)) + geom_point() +
           theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="top") +
           labs(x="Month",
                y="Percent of speeches about carbon tax") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format()) +
  scale_color_manual(name=NULL, values=c("Conservative" = "blue",
                                           "Liberal" = "red",
                                           "New Democratic Party" = "orange"))

Tokenizing a corpus

We can tokenize the entire corpus of 2018 speeches, so that one word appears on each line of the data frame.

speeches_tokenized <- speeches %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, speechtext) %>%
  filter(!is.na(speakername),
         speakerparty %in% c("Conservative", "New Democratic Party", "Liberal"),
         !is.na(maintopic)) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  select(speechdate, speakerparty, speakername, speakerriding, word)
## Joining, by = "word"
head(speeches_tokenized)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5

Counting word frequencies

Lets compare word use by party.

words_by_party <- speeches_tokenized %>% 
  group_by(speakerparty, word) %>%
  summarise(n=n()) %>%
  mutate(num = str_detect(word,"[0-9]+")) %>%
  filter(num == FALSE) %>%
  group_by(speakerparty) %>%
  mutate(word_freq=n/sum(n)) %>%
  select(speakerparty, word, word_freq) %>%
  filter(word_freq > 0.001) %>%
  spread(key=speakerparty, value=word_freq, fill=0)

  ggplot(words_by_party, aes(x=Conservative, y=Liberal)) + 
  geom_text(aes(label=word), colour="firebrick") +
  geom_abline(slope=1, intercept=0, linetype="dashed") +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_x_log10(labels=scales::percent_format()) +
  scale_y_log10(labels=scales::percent_format())
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis

What about incidence of a particular word by speaker?

Which MP talked most about the opioid crisis?

opioid_mps <- speeches %>% 
  group_by(speakerparty, speakername) %>%
  mutate(opioid = str_detect(speechtext, "opioid")) %>%
  summarise(speech_fraction=sum(opioid)/n()) %>%
  filter(speakerparty %in% c("Conservative", "New Democratic Party", "Liberal")) %>%
  arrange(desc(speech_fraction)) %>%
  top_n(10)
## Selecting by speech_fraction
  ggplot(opioid_mps, aes(x=reorder(speakername,speech_fraction), y=speech_fraction, fill=speakerparty)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(name=NULL, values=c("Conservative" = "blue",
                                           "Liberal" = "red",
                                           "New Democratic Party" = "orange")) + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(y="Percent of speeches containing 'opioid'",
       x=NULL) +
  theme_bw() +
    scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format())

Seniment analysis

The tidytext package comes with three sets of words that are coded to reflect sentiments. In the afinn sentiment-coded words, the sentiment scale runs from -5 to +5, with more positive numbers reflecting more positive sentiments. Lets take a look:

get_sentiments("afinn") %>% group_by(value) %>% summarise(word=first(word))
## # A tibble: 11 x 2
##    value word        
##    <dbl> <chr>       
##  1    -5 bastard     
##  2    -4 ass         
##  3    -3 abhor       
##  4    -2 abandon     
##  5    -1 absentee    
##  6     0 some kind   
##  7     1 aboard      
##  8     2 abilities   
##  9     3 admire      
## 10     4 amazing     
## 11     5 breathtaking

We can use these sentiment-rated words to analyze speech.

sentiments1 <- get_sentiments("afinn")
speech_sentiments <- speeches_tokenized %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% # This gets rid of joining words
  inner_join(sentiments1) %>%
  group_by(speakerparty) %>%
  summarise(meanscore = mean(value),
            sdev = sd(value),
            n = n(),
            se=sdev/sqrt(n)) %>%
  filter(n>100)

  ggplot(speech_sentiments) +
  geom_col(aes(x=speakerparty, y=meanscore)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(x=speakerparty, ymin=meanscore-1.96*se, ymax=meanscore+1.96*se)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(y="Mean AFINN seniment value")

We can look at the most positive and negative members of parliament

mp_sentiments <- speeches_tokenized %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% # This gets rid of joining words
  inner_join(sentiments1) %>%
  group_by(speakerparty,speakername) %>%
  summarise(meanscore = mean(value),
            n = n()) %>%
  filter(n>150)

  ggplot(mp_sentiments) +
  geom_col(aes(x=reorder(speakername, meanscore), y=meanscore, fill=speakerparty)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(y="Mean AFINN seniment value") +
  scale_fill_manual(name=NULL, values=c("Conservative" = "blue",
                                           "Liberal" = "red",
                                           "New Democratic Party" = "orange")) +
    theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank()) +
  labs(x="Speaker", y="Mean sentiment")

Lets put these on a map

Just for fun!

library(sf)
# Boundary files from from here: https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/geo/bound-limit/bound-limit-eng.cfm
shp <- read_sf("lfed000b16a_e/lfed000b16a_e.shp")
sents <- speeches_tokenized %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% # This gets rid of joining words
  inner_join(sentiments1) %>%
  group_by(speakerparty,speakerriding) %>%
  summarise(meanscore = mean(value),
            n = n()) %>%
  rename(FEDNAME = speakerriding) %>%
  mutate(FEDNAME = str_replace_all(FEDNAME,"[:^alpha:]",""))
shp_sents <- inner_join(shp %>%
                          mutate(FEDNAME = str_replace_all(FEDNAME,"[:^alpha:]","")), sents)
ggplot(shp_sents %>% filter(PRUID==35)) + geom_sf(aes(fill=meanscore)) +
  scale_fill_gradient2() +
  coord_sf(xlim=c(-85,-74),ylim=c(41,48),crs=4326)

What about a word cloud?

library(wordcloud)

# Let's plot nasty words used in parliament
nasty_words <- speeches_tokenized %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% # This gets rid of joining words

  filter(value <= -4) %>%
  group_by(word) %>%
  summarise(count=n())

pal <- brewer.pal(4, "Dark2")

nasty_words %>%
  with(wordcloud(word, count, random.order = FALSE, colors=pal))
